@flexiarg measurement/error-needs-structure-to-teach
@title A Bare Error Number Teaches Nothing — Record the Derivation With the Judgment
@sigils [Δ/🧾]
@keywords error, prediction, realised, derivation, learning signal, flight record, measurement, discharge judgment, propagate
@audience anyone recording predicted-vs-realised measurements a learner is supposed to eat
@tone corrective
@style pattern

! conclusion: When a record says predicted X, realised Y, error Z, the number Z alone is not a learning signal. Record the DERIVATION with the judgment — what the prediction was computed FROM, what the realisation actually measured, and the interpretation of their difference — so the error has structure to propagate. A measurement is a discharge judgment, not a number.

  + context: Loops that predict and then measure accumulate flight
    records. The cheap format — three floats and a timestamp — feels
    complete because the arithmetic checks out.

  + IF:
      You are recording a predicted value, a realised value, and their
      error, for a model or operator to learn from later.

  + HOWEVER:
      The error is a bare number: nothing says what the prediction was
      derived from, what the realisation measured, or what a zero (or a
      large) difference MEANS here — so identical errors from different
      causes are indistinguishable, and the learner has nothing to
      update on but magnitude.

  + THEN:
      Store the derivation alongside the judgment: the inputs and rule
      the prediction came from, the provenance of the realised reading,
      and an interpretation field (what this error licenses: model
      wrong / world moved / measurement broken / nothing-learned).
      The record is complete when a stranger can recompute the
      prediction and dispute the interpretation.

  + BECAUSE:
      Learning propagates through structure, not magnitude: a 0.0000
      error on a prediction derived from the answer teaches exactly
      nothing, and without the derivation nobody can see that this is
      what happened. (Kin: [[measurement/warrant-travels-with-the-number]],
      [[measurement/ghost-as-typed-sorry]].)

  + canonical-instance:
      M-first-flights (futon3c): the flight record prediction −4.9225 /
      realised −4.9225 / error 0.0000 that taught the model nothing —
      the loop anatomy existed but derivations were computed at the
      judgment site and thrown away (the mission's own diagnosis:
      "records are judgments without derivations"). The mission is
      satisfied exactly when records carry their derivations.
